// REFERENCE
// ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

/*
	All available commands are listed.

	Keyjazz keys cannot have modifiers ("ctrl", "alt", or "shift").

	You can create multiple bindings for a command with the following syntax:
		"patternstack_back" : [ "escape", "left alt" ]

	Commands can be commented out.

	A command with an empty string ("") will be skipped.

	The hotkey string for a command can be in any order, ie:
		"foo" : "e ctrl"
	or
		"foo" : "ctrl e"

	You can use an ASCII character for a hotkey, ie:
		"wave_next" : "<"
	If you use an ASCII character without any modifiers then the hotkey will be case-sensitive;
	The character may require pressing shift.

	If modifiers are used, then the hotkey is virtual and is not case sensitive, ie:
		"interpolate" : "i ctrl"
		"interpolate" : "I ctrl"
	-- These two are the same.

	You can also use these virtual keys:
		backspace, tab, clear, enter
		pause
		capslock
		escape, space
		pageup, pagedown, end, home
		left, up, right, down
		select, print, execute, printscreen
		insert, delete
		help
		numpad0, numpad1, numpad2, numpad3, numpad4, numpad5, numpad6, numpad7, numpad8, numpad9
		multiply, add, separator, subtract, decimal, divide
		f1, f2, f3, f4, f5, f6, f7, f8, f9, f10, f11, f12, f13, f14, f15, f16
		numlock, scrolllock
		oem_1		// ';:' for US
		oem_plus	// '+' any country
		oem_comma	// ',' any country
		oem_minus	// '-' any country
		oem_period	// '.' any country
		oem_2		// '/?' for US
		oem_3		// '`~' for US
		oem_4		// '[{' for US
		oem_5		// '\|' for US
		oem_6		// ']}' for US
		oem_7		// ''"' for US
		oem_8		//

	The "BUILTINS" comment in each section lists hotkeys that cannot be modified, because they need to
	support some special behaviour. An example of this would be the Up/Down/Left/Right keys in the
	Pattern Editor, because they support repetition and diagonal motion.
	Your custom bindings should not conflict with these keys.
*/

